    <!-- ============================================
         THE TEST
         ============================================ -->
    
    <div class="panel">
      <h4>Why This Matters</h4>
      <p>The tragedy of Genesis 3 is larger than the entrance of sin: humanity rejected its vocation. Rather than ruling creation on God's behalf, the image-bearers sought to define good and evil independently of God — and every exile, failed kingdom, and broken covenant that follows grows out of that first rebellion.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="pattern-summary"><strong>Pattern Scorecard:</strong> ✓ Garden · ✓ Serpent · ✓ Test · ✓ Curse · ✓ Eastward exile · ✓ De-creation waters · ✓ City against God · ✓ Seed of hope</div>

    <section class="theology-card" id="serpent">
      <h2 class="section-title"><span class="section-icon">🐍</span> The Test in the Garden</h2>
      <blockquote class="scripture-quote">
        Now the serpent was more crafty than any of the wild animals the LORD God had made.
        <span class="reference">Genesis 3:1</span>
      </blockquote>
      <p>Genesis 3 opens with a pun the English hides. The couple were <span class="hebrew-inline" lang="he" dir="rtl">עֲרוּמִּים</span> (<em>arummim</em>, "naked," 2:25); the serpent is <span class="hebrew-inline" lang="he" dir="rtl">עָרוּם</span> (<em>arum</em>, "crafty," 3:1). The wordplay signals what kind of story this is: the innocent and exposed are about to meet the shrewd, and the question on the table is <em>wisdom</em> — where it comes from and how it is gained.</p>
      <p>The forbidden tree is "the tree of the knowledge of good and evil" — knowledge language the Old Testament elsewhere associates with the discernment kings and judges need (1 Kgs 3:9). The issue is not that God withholds wisdom from His images; it is <em>how</em> wisdom is to be had. Will the image-bearers receive it from God, in God's time, at God's table — or seize it on the serpent's terms, "taking" what looks "good… a delight to the eyes… desirable to make one wise" (3:6)?</p>
      <p>The priestly failure precedes the eating. Adam, charged in 2:15 to <em>guard</em> sacred space, stands by while an unclean, deceiving creature enters the garden and slanders God to his wife. The image-bearers who were to rule the beasts are instead ruled by one.</p>
      <div class="key-insight">
        <strong>The test is the template.</strong>
        A test over trust and wisdom in sacred space — this scene will replay at Sinai, in the wilderness, in the promised land, and finally in another wilderness where the Last Adam answers the tempter with trust (Matt 4). Genesis 3 is not just the first sin; it is the pattern every "new Adam" will face.
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================
         EXILE EAST
         ============================================ -->
    <section class="theology-card" id="exile-east">
      <h2 class="section-title"><span class="section-icon">🚪</span> Curse and Eastward Exile</h2>
      <p>The consequences of Genesis 3 track the commission of Genesis 1–2 point for point, unraveling it. Fruitfulness is now attended by pain; rule of the ground becomes toil against thorns; the harmonious partnership of the image-bearers turns to grasping and blame; and the humans made from dust hear the sentence: "to dust you shall return." Each element of the vocation is bent but — notably — not revoked.</p>
      <p>The climactic loss is spatial. God drives the humans out of the garden, and the direction is marked: cherubim are stationed <span class="hebrew-inline" lang="he" dir="rtl">מִקֶּדֶם</span> (<em>miqqedem</em>, "at the east") of Eden with a flaming sword, guarding the way back to the Tree of Life (3:24). Exile from sacred space — the loss of access to God's presence — is the Bible's first and deepest definition of death.</p>
      <div class="pattern-summary"><strong>Pattern Summary:</strong> Watch the compass in Genesis 3–11. Adam and Eve are driven out eastward; Cain settles "east of Eden" (4:16); humanity migrates "from the east" to build Babel (11:2). Eastward movement becomes the Bible's shorthand for exile from presence — which is why the Tabernacle, Temple, and Ezekiel's visionary temple are all entered from the east, retracing the way back in.</div>
      <div class="cross-ref"><strong>Cross-reference:</strong> The cherubim with the sword guarding Eden's entrance become the embroidered cherubim on the Tabernacle veil (Exod 26:31) — the barrier that stands until it tears (Matt 27:51).</div>
    </section>

    <hr class="star-divider" aria-hidden="true">

    <!-- ============================================
         SIN SPREADS
         ============================================ -->
    <section class="theology-card" id="spread">
      <h2 class="section-title"><span class="section-icon">🩸</span> Sin Spreads: Cain to Lamech</h2>
      <blockquote class="scripture-quote">
        Sin is crouching at your door; it desires to have you, but you must rule over it.
        <span class="reference">Genesis 4:7</span>
      </blockquote>
      <p>Genesis 4 personifies sin for the first time: it is <span class="hebrew-inline" lang="he" dir="rtl">רֹבֵץ</span> (<em>rovets</em>) — "crouching" at the door like a predator, and Cain is told he must <em>rule</em> it (the same verb as the Genesis 1 commission). The image-bearer's rule has a new object: the beast is no longer only outside him. And crucially, the narrative frames Cain's moment as a genuine test, not a foregone conclusion: "if you do well, will you not be accepted?" (4:7). It is not inevitable that Cain replay his parents' failure — each generation faces its own Eden. Cain fails by choice, and the ground that was cursed <em>because of</em> Adam now opens its mouth to receive a brother's blood <em>from</em> Cain's hand.</p>
      <p>Genesis 4–5 then sorts humanity into a tale of two seeds — the serpent's and the woman's (3:15) — traced through two genealogies. Cain's line runs seven generations to Lamech and his three sons: city-building, name-making, escalating violence, seventy-sevenfold vengeance sung as the Bible's first recorded song (4:17–24). Seth's line runs ten generations to Noah and <em>his</em> three sons, carrying the image (5:1–3), the calling on Yahweh's name (4:26), and a father's hope of comfort from the curse (5:29). The lines are defined not by ancestry but by allegiance: Cain was born of the woman and aligned himself with the snake. Every character in the rest of the Bible will stand in this fork.</p>
      <div class="key-insight">
        <strong>Filled with the wrong thing.</strong>
        Humanity does carry out a version of the commission: they multiply, they fill the earth, they build. But what fills the earth is <span class="hebrew-inline" lang="he" dir="rtl">חָמָס</span> (<em>hamas</em>, violence) instead of blessing. De-creation is not the absence of human culture; it is human culture running on the serpent's operating system.
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================
         THE FLOOD
         ============================================ -->
    <section class="theology-card" id="flood">
      <h2 class="section-title"><span class="section-icon">🌊</span> The Flood as De-Creation</h2>
      <p>The Flood narrative is told in the vocabulary of Genesis 1 run backward. The <span class="hebrew-inline" lang="he" dir="rtl">מַבּוּל</span> (<em>mabbul</em>) is not merely heavy weather; it is the structural collapse of creation's architecture. The "springs of the great deep" burst open and "the windows of the heavens" are opened (7:11) — the waters below and the waters above, separated on day two, come back together. Dry land, uncovered on day three, disappears. The creatures of days five and six are blotted out in reverse order of their creation. The world returns toward <em>tohu vavohu</em>.</p>
      <table class="pattern-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Creation (Genesis 1)</th><th>De-Creation (Genesis 6–7)</th><th>Re-Creation (Genesis 8–9)</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Waters above and below separated (day 2)</td><td>Waters above and below reunite (7:11)</td><td>Windows and springs closed (8:2)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Dry land appears (day 3)</td><td>All high land covered (7:19–20)</td><td>Dry land reappears (8:13–14)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Spirit/wind (<span class="hebrew-inline" lang="he" dir="rtl">רוּחַ</span>) over the waters (1:2)</td><td>—</td><td>God sends a <em>ruach</em> over the earth (8:1)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Be fruitful, multiply, fill (1:28)</td><td>Earth "filled with violence" (6:11)</td><td>Blessing reissued verbatim (9:1)</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>Genesis 8–9 then replays creation deliberately: wind over the waters, land emerging, creatures coming out to swarm, the blessing of 1:28 reissued to Noah word for word. It is the Bible's first "Creation 2.0" attempt — and its first demonstration that starting over is not enough. The flood changes the world but not the heart: "the inclination of the human heart is evil from youth" stands on both sides of the water (6:5; 8:21). Within a chapter, the new Adam of the new creation is drunk and uncovered in a garden-vineyard, and a son is cursed.</p>
      <div class="pattern-summary"><strong>The Melody of Genesis 1–11:</strong> Creation and blessing → folly, test, and failure → de-creation → a remnant rescued → new creation and blessing through covenant. Genesis 1–11 runs this cycle three times over — creation to flood, flood to Babel, Babel to Abram — and composes it with recurring number-patterns (3+1, 7, 10: seven-day creation, Cain's seven generations plus three sons, Adam-to-Noah's ten generations plus three sons, Shem-to-Abram's ten). This is not just structure; it is the Bible's thematic melody, and later books — Ezekiel above all — will replay it movement for movement. The loop closes only when someone passes through the waters without failing on the far side.</div>
    </section>

    <hr class="star-divider" aria-hidden="true">

    <!-- ============================================
         BABEL
         ============================================ -->
    <section class="theology-card" id="babel">
      <h2 class="section-title"><span class="section-icon">🗼</span> Babel: Empire Instead of Eden</h2>
      <blockquote class="scripture-quote">
        "Come, let us build ourselves a city, with a tower that reaches to the heavens, so that we may make a name for ourselves; otherwise we will be scattered over the face of the whole earth."
        <span class="reference">Genesis 11:4</span>
      </blockquote>
      <p>Babel is de-creation in its mature, organized form. The commission said <em>fill the earth</em>; Babel's builders unite precisely so they will <em>not</em> be scattered. The commission made humanity God's image, carrying His name; Babel manufactures "a name for ourselves." The tower — in Mesopotamian terms a ziggurat, an artificial mountain meant to join heaven and earth — is a counterfeit Eden: humanity constructing its own sacred mountain, on its own terms, for its own glory.</p>
      <div class="word-study">
        <h4>Word Study: <span class="hebrew-inline" lang="he" dir="rtl">בָּבֶל</span> (bavel) and <span class="hebrew-inline" lang="he" dir="rtl">בָּלַל</span> (balal) — "Babylon" and "confuse"</h4>
        <p>The city's residents heard <em>bab-ilu</em>, "gate of the gods." The narrator hears a pun: <em>bavel</em> sounds like <em>balal</em>, "to confuse, mix." The self-proclaimed gate of heaven becomes the Bible's byword for confusion — and "Babylon" becomes Scripture's permanent name for empire organized against God, from Nebuchadnezzar to Revelation 17–18. Movement 6 (exile) and Movement 9 (Babylon's fall) both hang on this word.</p>
      </div>
      <p>God's response is judgment that serves the commission: the languages are confused and the nations are scattered "over the face of all the earth" (11:9) — filled at last, but as fragments. The Table of Nations in Genesis 10 lists seventy peoples now estranged from God and each other. The creation project has not merely stalled; it has produced its own rival.</p>
      <div class="cross-ref"><strong>Cross-reference:</strong> Pentecost answers Babel point for point: one Spirit descends, every nation hears in its own tongue, and three thousand are gathered rather than scattered (Acts 2:5–11) — Movement 8's opening scene.</div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================
         THE OPEN QUESTION
         ============================================ -->
    <section class="theology-card" id="question">
      <h2 class="section-title"><span class="section-icon">🌱</span> The Question Genesis 3–11 Leaves Open</h2>
      <p>For all its darkness, this movement refuses despair, and it does so in two quiet ways. First, judgment is always tempered with grace: garments for the exiles, a mark for Cain, an ark through the waters, a covenant with every living creature and a bow hung in the clouds (9:8–17) — God binding <em>Himself</em> to creation's future before anyone asks. Second, the narrative keeps a genealogy running like a fuse: Seth, Enosh, Noah, Shem… a line the reader is taught to watch.</p>
      <div class="grid-2">
        <div class="panel"><h4>What Changed?</h4><p><strong>Before:</strong> Humanity walked with God.<br><strong>After:</strong> Humanity carries exile wherever it goes.</p></div>
        <div class="panel"><h4>Echoes Ahead</h4><p>Cain anticipates Israel · Babel anticipates Babylon · the flood anticipates the Exodus waters · Adam anticipates every king · Jesus succeeds where Adam failed (Hosea 6:7; Rev 17–18; Matt 4).</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="pivot-box">
        <span class="pivot-label">Where the Story Goes Next</span>
        <p>Genesis 3:15 promises that the woman's <span class="hebrew-inline" lang="he" dir="rtl">זֶרַע</span> (<em>zera</em>, seed) will crush the serpent's head, though at cost. Every genealogy in Genesis is the narrator tracking that seed through the wreckage. By the end of chapter 11 the line has narrowed to one childless couple in Ur — and the question of the whole movement comes to a point: <strong>where will the faithful image-bearer come from?</strong></p>
      </div>
      <p>Genesis 3–11 thus ends the way a well-built act ends: with the problem fully stated and the stage stripped. Creation is broken at every level — heart, family, ground, worship, culture, cosmos. Starting over with everyone (the Flood) has been tried. What God does next is stranger and slower: He starts over with <em>one family</em>, for the sake of all the scattered ones.</p>
      <p class="takeaway">De-creation is real, but it is never total: the curse runs deep, and the promise runs deeper. Movement 3 follows the seed to Abraham.</p>
    </section>

